<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-224-174 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 388 517</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  Feb 11 1991* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1991.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Moscow: some joint ventures to benefit from new tax laws.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Tchashchin, Kirill.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Soviet UnionJoint VentureTax LawComputer industryGovernment RegulationInternational Trade.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>MOSCOW: SOME JOINT VENTURES TO BENEFIT FROM NEW TAX LAWS 02/11/91 MOSCOW,U.S.S.R., 1991 FEB 11 (NB) -- Several existing technology joint ventures(JVs) in Soviet Union will benefit from newly introduced taxation rules.andM;New regulations, to be released soon, will waive taxes on revenues spent onlocal investing and scientific research.andP;  In addition to that, foreignentities from Austria, Britain, Finland and a number of other East Europeancountries will pay no taxes here according to existing double taxationtreaties.andM;According to local industry experts, two existing communications ventures aswell as a number of big hardware dealers including JV Intermicro -- biggestat the moment -- will enjoy lower taxes as a result of this last decision.andM;(Kirill Tchashchin/19910211)</TEXT></DOC>